review_blob: Decadence hardly begins to describe this one. Enjoyed in a snifter, courtesy of the owner at One Mile House in NYC. Has a great dark brown, ruby-tinged color to it. Smell has a combo of yeast and bananas, but not strong, more subtle like dried bananas. Described as a quad, my mind had a hard time with the flavor until reading the bottle yielded that "ah-ha!" moment - molasses. Finishes with a slight bit of alcohol burn, but very, very tiny compared to its big 12% ABV. Overall one of the best beers Ive had.

Seems to be awesome for one specific purpose - providing some of the flavors that the depth and thump of a real quad or BCBS would provide.

My first mistake was not reading ratings about it being a cork rocket. With the final twist of the cage, I was grateful it wasnt pointing at my face or Id be blind in one eye. Its annoyingly carbonated, both in the pour and the body. However, once in my snifter, I swirled out most of the bubbles in order to get to the real flavors. 

I found the nose to be delightfully wine/grape oriented, with no hint of it being 11.25% ABV. You could tell it had a lot of quad to its base, but it was a thinned-out version of one with none of the usual complexity. It goes down easy, but once youve swallowed it ... wait for it ... theres that warming bourbon burn left behind. I personally found it to be good, not great, but my wife absolutely loved it as someone who likes those flavors but is put off by more than about 2 ozs of a BCBS-class beer.

beer_name: De Proefbrouwerij / Hair of the Dog Flanders Fred

review_blob: First impression was that it had a bit of a bitter smell to it, which didnt seem to match up with my expectations of the deScription and the pour. It came out light and slightly bubbly, like a refreshing cider. You definitely could taste the fruit, but as a long-time pomegranate fan, I didnt get as much of a tartness that I was looking for. I guess the honey really cut into that. Wasnt too bad overall, but its not one Id actively pursue in the future.

Right off the pour, the alcohol notes hit you out of the glass. Not tame at 9%, it smells like it should be 14%. It comes out jet black, letting you know it means business. However, the taste is rich and smooth, with the heavy malt presence trying to tell you it doesnt even know what a hop is, and will kick your ass if you try to explain it.

I dont have a great sense of smell, but I could swear I noted apricot in this 2012 effort. Had a good hop aroma, but not too piney. It had some chardonnay characteristics, most notably its dryness on the tongue. Foamed up quickly when poured, but it didnt last long. Overall Id say I enjoyed it, just not at its price point. If youre buyin, Im drinkin.

Enjoyed by its lonesome in a pint glass, late night paired with some Demetri Martin standup on TV.

On first pour, you get a strong whiff of the brown sugar, then when you get closer, you get that old familiar Lagunitas-blast of hops. Its one of those perfect-pour beers; just throw it down the middle, and it will perfectly sort out two fingers of foam atop a caramel-colored body. Upon first taste, it seems a bit sweet, but the more you have, the more the lingering hops begin to dominate the profile, giving you a terrific malt/hop combination of flavors. For so much flavor, its easy to gulp it down, but it deserves to be savored.

You really can smell the honey, even with a below-average nose like mine. On first taste, it comes across as a beer that has high gravity for the sake of high gravity, but once you let it slide down your throat, you get that nice, warm feeling that makes you feel relaxed and easy-going.

The taste of this beer was surprising given how relatively light its texture and aroma was. You get a slight nip on first taste, with the hops making their presence felt. However, they go away quickly, and are smoothly replaced by the smoky malts that you expect. Another fine entry from one of my favorite regional breweries.

Tried this for the first time last night, and was very pleasantly surprised. After getting shut out from a tasting of a rare German lent beer, I needed something to distract me from my misery. Given the rich, dark color, I was surprised it didnt have more of an aroma. However, upon first taste, I was blown away by how smooth it was, and all I kept saying was "wow, what a great bourbon bite on the finish." As it warmed in my tulip glass, the taste got better and better. If I didnt have to drive home, I would have enjoyed one or two more of these.
